<http://datadock.io/kal/local_data_1/id/resource/monument_record_no/299M> <http://datadock.io/kal/local_data_1/id/definition/monument_desc> "House. A large medieval hall, noted by Braikenridge in particular for its north-west to south-east alignment. Trusses springing off corbels set well below wall tops. Three tiers of windbraces each side. Numerous redundant corbels around the walls, possibly brought from elsewhere. Flagstone floor. \r\nAt the north-west end, a 6-light window at higher level, two-centred heads within an overall square headed frame. Above, another window, shallow segmental two-centred head, 2 lights with some tracery. Door at north-west end of south-west wall led to a cellar. First-floor access in end of north-east wall leading to the adjacent dwelling house above stairs, a doorway below to a passage leading from the dwelling house to the street. \r\nHigh in the south-east end wall, a 3-light window, two-arched heads in a square frame. Panelling around all three walls at that end. \r\nSaid to have been the residence of the younger Sir John Knight, who was Mayor in 1670. The house contained a full-height chimney-piece (Arch.El.No.1031A)."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> <http://datadock.io/kal/local_data_1/id/dataset/Bristol_Monuments.csv>.
